description:
secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs:151-155, in `WritableSecretStore::put`:

```rust
let s = std::str::from_utf8(value.as_bytes())
    .map_err(|_| { SecretError::DecodeFailed(...) })?
    .to_owned();
```

`.to_owned()` on a `&str` allocates a fresh `String` containing a plaintext copy of the secret. That `String` is then moved into the spawn_blocking closure and dropped at the end of the closure without zeroization. The original `SecretValue` (which IS zeroizing — wraps `Zeroizing<Vec<u8>>` via secretx-core/src/lib.rs:53-57) is preserved, but a non-zeroizing duplicate of the secret bytes lives on the heap for the duration of the keyring write, then is freed without being scrubbed.

The `keyring::Entry::set_password` API requires `&str` (keyring-3.6.3/src/lib.rs API), so a fresh string allocation is unavoidable. The leakable copy can be minimized by wrapping in `zeroize::Zeroizing<String>` instead of plain `String`:

```rust
use zeroize::Zeroizing;
let s: Zeroizing<String> = Zeroizing::new(
    std::str::from_utf8(value.as_bytes())
        .map_err(|_| SecretError::DecodeFailed(...))?
        .to_owned()
);
// then call entry.set_password(&s) — Deref<Target=String> works
```

zeroize is already a workspace dep (Cargo.toml workspace.dependencies includes `zeroize`).

Same issue exists in secretx-desktop/src/lib.rs:139-145 — fix should be applied uniformly. Do not file a separate desktop issue from this epic; note as cross-crate.

Trigger: process memory dump after a put() call captures the plaintext secret. Maintenance consequence: every audit/compliance review will flag this; the project's stated zeroize discipline is broken on the keyring write path.
